result.execSummary:
On one or more charges, the deferred prosecution or sentencing agreement(s) on this case were fulfilled, and the charge(s) were dismissed.

The defendant Aaron R. Hardy was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Intent. Contribute/Delinquency Child [Modifiers: Repeater], a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 948.40(1).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

miscConds.notes: Defendant shall not commit any criminal offenses during the period of this agreement.  Defendant shall notify the Taylor County District Attorney's Office and Clerk of Court's office of any change of address within 10 days.  Defendant must successfully complete the two year probation period and all required conditions of probation.  Defendant shall comply with his bond.
Defendant shall undergo an AODA and follow through with any recommendations at the discretion of probation.   Proof of assessment must be provided to the Taylor County District Attorney's office.

judgments.dispoDesc: Pursuant to an agreement and on motion of the State, the court granted a deferred entry of judgment for a period of two years.  Upon successful completion of the agreement, the State will move to dismiss the misdemeanor charge.
